&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; On Fri, Apr 17, 2009 at 2:48 PM, Bill de hOra &lt;bill@... 
&gt; &lt;mailto:bill%40dehora.net&gt;&gt; wrote:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; Kris Zyp wrote:
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt;&gt; The elegance of JSON in a REST architecture is that JSON implicitly
&gt;  &gt;&gt; provides link relations. I am skeptical that we need yet another link
&gt;  &gt;&gt; relation mechanism in addition to the natural links are already
&gt;  &gt;&gt; defined by JSON itself.
&gt;  &gt;
&gt;  &gt; This assumption was a huge mistake in the XML community; I hope JSON
&gt;  &gt; users aren&#39;t doing the same thing.
&gt; 
&gt; Can you elaborate a bit more on which assumption was a huge mistake
&gt; and how the problems that assumption caused manifested themselves?

That being a child element entails cardinality or relational or other 
semantics wrt a parent element other than what XML specifies.

&lt;parent&gt;
   &lt;child&gt;

&lt;document&gt;
   &lt;chapter&gt;

&lt;folder&gt;
  &lt;file&gt;

&lt;car&gt;
  &lt;wheel&gt;

&lt;entry&gt;
   &lt;author&gt;

These have no semantics beyond XML parsing. Unless you document the 
semantics for your format. If you want to define semantics a machine can 
automatically leverage, a language like RDF or KIF would be better.

I don&#39;t buy that JSON provides any such entailments either.

Bill
